💡 DETAILED ANALYSIS:
The document is essentially a raw data dump in a tabular format. While the semantic density is high—meaning there is a lot of specific, factual information—the structure is highly detrimental to RAG performance. Large language models (LLMs) often fail to accurately associate rows with headers when reading complex tables from PDFs, leading to "hallucinated" associations between an employee name and the wrong serial number or link.

The biggest strength is the granularity of the data (Serial Numbers, Purchase Dates, Models). However, the critical issue is the lack of semantic structure. A RAG pipeline will treat this as a single, massive block of text, making it nearly impossible to query specific questions like "Which employees have returned their devices?" or "What is the status of the MacBook Pro 14 assigned to X?" without significant pre-processing. The document currently lacks any narrative or hierarchical structure, which is essential for effective retrieval.

🔧 RECOMMENDED CHUNKING STRATEGY:
Do not use standard text-based chunking.

Method: Convert the source to a structured format (CSV or JSON).
Strategy: Use "Record-Level Chunking." Each row should be treated as a single, discrete chunk.
Metadata Injection: For every chunk (row), inject the column headers as part of the text string (e.g., "Employee: X | Model: MacBook Pro 14 | Purchased: Feb 2025 | Serial: xxxxxxxxxx | Status: Active"). This ensures the LLM has full context for every individual record retrieved.
